nt did not take the Hollywood route to success. What emerges is a strong feeling for the character of the man as well as for a remarkable career in British cinema.The book will appeal to admirers, researchers and students alike. Making use of hitherto unseen original materials from Anderson’s extensive personal and professional records, it is most valuable as a study of how the films came about: the production problems involved, the collaborative input of others, as well as the completed films’ promotion and reception.It also offers a finely argued take on the whole issue of film authorship, and achieves the rare feat of being academically authoritative whilst also being completely accessible. It prompts renewed respect for the man and the artist and a desire to watch the films all over again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture industryzGreat Britain. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aBritish cinema.  aFree Cinema.  aLindsay Anderson.  adirector.  afilm authorship.  aproduction problems.1 aGourdin-Sangouard, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannan, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHannan, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzod, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagee, Karl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMagee, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614160640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526141606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526141606/original  